<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,361,854]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,592,618]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Etymology</emphasis>
:—This species is named after the Lemhi Shoshone woman, Sacajawea (1788–1812?), who served as guide and interpreter for Lewis and Clark (
<bibRefCitation author="Mann, J. W. W." box="[768,908,632,658]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref4011" refString="Mann, J. W. W. (2004) Sacajawea's people: the Lemhi Shoshones and the Salmon River country. University of Nebraska Press, Lincoln." type="book" year="2004">Mann 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,361,854]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,374,670,696]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Observations:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[403,672,671,696]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="sacajaweae">
<emphasis box="[403,672,671,696]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Stauroneis sacajaweae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bahls, L." box="[881,1096,670,696]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref3484" refString="Bahls, L. (2010) Stauroneis in the Northern Rockies - 50 species of Stauroneis sensu stricto from western Montana, northern Idaho, northeastern Washington and southwestern Alberta, including 16 species described as new. Vol. 4 In: Bahls, L. (Ed.), Northwest Diatoms, Montana Diatom Collection, Helena, 179 pp." type="book" year="2010">Bahls (2010: 155)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authority="Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot (2004: 72)" authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot" authorityPageNumber="72" authorityYear="2004" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="subhyperborea">
<emphasis box="[1139,1345,671,696]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. subhyperborea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver, B. &amp; Beyens, L. &amp; Lange-Bertalot, H." pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref4449" refString="Van de Vijver, B., Beyens, L. &amp; Lange-Bertalot, H. (2004) The Genus Stauroneis in the Arctic and (Sub-) Antarctic Regions. Bibliotheca Diatomologica, Band 51. J. Cramer, Berlin, 317 pp." type="book" year="2004">Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot (2004: 72)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the 
<collectingRegion box="[768,874,709,735]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Montana</collectingRegion>
specimens have a wider stauros and distinctly higher stria and areola densities than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot" authorityYear="2004" box="[605,816,748,773]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="subhyperborea">
<emphasis box="[605,816,748,773]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. subhyperborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Besides the 
<typeStatus box="[980,1032,748,774]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">type</typeStatus>
locality—which it shares with 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="clarkii">S. clarkii</taxonomicName>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[257,419,786,811]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="sacajaweae">S. sacajaweae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
has been collected from a seep along the Going-To-The-Sun Road in Glacier National Park, 
<collectingRegion box="[219,326,828,854]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Montana</collectingRegion>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[338,473,825,854]" degrees="48.7381" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" precision="5" value="48.7381">
48.7381 
<superScript attach="left" box="[433,441,825,839]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">o</superScript>
N
</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[485,640,825,854]" degrees="113.7456" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" precision="5" value="-113.7456">
113.7456 
<superScript attach="left" box="[593,601,825,839]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">o</superScript>
W
</geoCoordinate>
.
</paragraph>
